# AWS Configuration - Choose ONE method:

# ==========================================
# METHOD 1: AWS LOGIN (RECOMMENDED - Easiest!)
# ==========================================
# Simply run: aws login
# That's it! No need to set anything below.
# AWS CLI handles everything automatically.
#
# For SSO/IAM Identity Center:
#   aws login --profile my-profile
#
# The 'aws login' command is the modern, easy way!

# ==========================================
# METHOD 2: Environment Variables (Alternative)
# ==========================================
# Uncomment and set these if NOT using 'aws login':
# AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=your_access_key_here
# AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=your_secret_key_here
# AWS_DEFAULT_REGION=us-east-1

# ==========================================
# METHOD 3: AWS Profile (Alternative)
# ==========================================
# Uncomment if using a named profile:
# AWS_PROFILE=your-profile-name

# AWS Session Token (for temporary credentials)
# AWS_SESSION_TOKEN=your_session_token

# Truffle Configuration (optional)
# TRUFFLE_DEFAULT_REGION=us-east-1
# TRUFFLE_DEFAULT_OUTPUT=table
# TRUFFLE_CACHE_ENABLED=true
# TRUFFLE_CACHE_TTL=300

# Go Build Configuration
GOOS=linux
GOARCH=amd64

# Development
# TRUFFLE_DEBUG=false
# TRUFFLE_VERBOSE=false

# ==========================================
# SETUP INSTRUCTIONS:
# ==========================================
# EASIEST: Just run 'aws login' - no file needed!
#
# OR if you need environment variables:
# 1. Copy this file: cp .env.example .env
# 2. Edit .env with your AWS credentials
# 3. Never commit .env to version control!
# 4. Source it: source .env
# 5. Or use: export $(cat .env | xargs)
# ==========================================
